  "text": "HTTP request header injection validation in Envoy v1.31.2 is implemented through a comprehensive validation framework with multiple layers:\n\n## Core Header Validation Framework\n\nThe validation starts in `source/common/http/header_utility.cc` which provides foundational validation functions:\n- `checkRequiredRequestHeaders()` - Verifies presence of mandatory headers like :method and :path\n- `checkValidRequestHeaders()` - Validates header names and values for valid characters\n- `headerNameIsValid()` - Uses HTTP/2 semantics (via nghttp2/http2::adapter) to validate header names, allowing only RFC-compliant token characters\n- `headerValueIsValid()` - Uses http2::adapter::HeaderValidator::IsValidHeaderValue() with ObsText support to validate header values\n- `requestHeadersValid()` - Validates host authority and method token validity\n\n## Header Validator Extension System\n\n`source/extensions/http/header_validators/envoy_default/header_validator.cc` implements the Envoy Default Header Validator which:\n- Validates pseudo-headers (:method, :authority, :scheme, :path, :protocol, :status)\n- Implements `sanitizeHeadersWithUnderscores()` - Drops or rejects headers with underscores based on configuration\n- Implements `sanitizePathWithFragment()` - Removes URL fragments from paths\n- Implements `sanitizeEncodedSlashes()` - Handles escaped slashes in paths\n- Uses character tables (character_tables.h) to enforce RFC-compliant character sets\n\n## Protocol-Specific Validators\n\nHTTP/1.1 validation (`source/extensions/http/header_validators/envoy_default/http1_header_validator.cc`):\n- `validateTransferEncodingHeader()` - Only allows 'chunked' encoding per HTTP/1.1 spec\n- `transformRequestHeaders()` - Applies sanitization and normalization\n- `sanitizeContentLength()` - Removes zero content-length from CONNECT requests\n\nHTTP/2 validation (`source/extensions/http/header_validators/envoy_default/http2_header_validator.cc`):\n- `transformRequestHeaders()` - Sanitizes headers, handles path normalization\n- Transforms H/2 extended CONNECT to H/1 UPGRADE format\n- Validates protocol-specific pseudo-headers\n\n## Codec-Level Validation\n\nBoth `source/common/http/http1/codec_impl.cc` and `source/common/http/http2/codec_impl.cc` perform validation before encoding:\n- Check required headers (checkRequiredRequestHeaders)\n- Validate header characters (checkValidRequestHeaders)\n- In HTTP/1, `onHeaderValue()` validates each header value has valid characters\n\n## Internal Header Stripping\n\n`source/common/http/conn_manager_utility.cc` implements critical injection prevention:\n- `cleanInternalHeaders()` - Removes internal Envoy headers from edge requests to prevent client injection:\n  - x-envoy-decorator-operation\n  - x-envoy-downstream-service-cluster\n  - x-envoy-downstream-service-node\n  - x-envoy-original-path\n  - x-envoy-retry-on, x-envoy-retry-grpc-on, x-envoy-max-retries\n  - x-envoy-upstream-* headers\n  - And other internal headers via route configuration\n\n## Request Processing Chain\n\n`source/common/http/conn_manager_impl.cc` orchestrates the validation:\n1. `ActiveStream::decodeHeaders()` receives request headers\n2. `validateHeaders()` is called which:\n   - Invokes header_validator_->validateRequestHeaders()\n   - Applies transformations via header_validator_->transformRequestHeaders()\n   - Returns error (400 Bad Request) on validation failure\n3. After validation, `mutateRequestHeaders()` is called to:\n   - Apply additional header mutations\n   - Call `cleanInternalHeaders()` to remove internal headers from edge requests\n\n## Security Features\n\n- Forbidden character validation prevents header injection via control characters (\\x00, \\x0A, \\x0D)\n- Underscore handling configurable (ALLOW, DROP_HEADER, REJECT)\n- Path normalization prevents encoding tricks\n- Extended CONNECT and H/2 upgrade transformations prevent protocol confusion attacks\n- Runtime feature flags allow security-sensitive behavior to be toggled without recompilation\n\nThe design follows defense-in-depth with validation at multiple layers: codec level, header validator level, and connection manager level, ensuring injected headers are caught before reaching upstream services."
}

